In France, voting is traditionally an untechnological experience: voters enter an isolated cabin and put a preprinted sheet in an envelope indicating the chosen candidate.
After the official verification of his identity by the officials, the elector deposits the envelope in the urn and signs the electoral register.
French electoral law in France codifies procedures quite strict.
Since 1988 the electoral polls must be transparent so that voters and observers can testify that no envelopes are present at the start of the voting and that no other envelopes are included other than those of the voters, duly counted and authorized.
