Much of the interpretations of determinism have in common two general ideas: one is that the development of technology itself follows a path that goes far beyond political and cultural influence, and the other is that technology has in turn of the “effects” on societies that is inherent, rather than socially conditioned and social.
For example, we can say that the car necessarily involve the development of the road network.
However, a national road network for only a few cars is not economically sustainable and therefore new production methods are being developed to reduce the costs related to car ownership.
