The most easily accessible plant resources would have been the proteins in leaves and legumes, but for primates like us they are difficult to digest, unless they are cooked.
Animal foods (such as ants, thermites, eggs) are not only easy to digest, but they provide a high amount of protein, containing all essential amino acids.
In view of this, it should come as no surprise that our ancestors solved their “protein problem” in a way that savanna chimpanzees do today.
Sleep interruption is the process of intentional awakening that occurs during the normal sleep period, followed by which a sleep recovery is followed (10–60 minutes later).
This process can be easily put into practice using a relatively silent alarm clock to bring you to a state of consciousness, without waking up completely.
If you decide to reset the clock in sleep, you can put it on the other side of the room, so you will be forced to get out of bed to turn it off.
Other options focused on biorhythm include consuming many fluids before bedtime (especially water or tea (known for its diuretic properties), which force them to get up to urinate).
