The Sundarbans are the largest mangrove coastal band of mangrove in the world. It extends 80 km (50 mi) from the coast in the hinterland of Bangladesh and India.
The Sundarbans have been declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site by UNESCO, and the part of forest included in Indian territory is named Sundarbans National Park.
However, the forests are not only made up of mangrove marshes: they also contain what remains of the imposing jungles that once covered the Gange plain.
The Sundarbans cover an area of 3,850 km², of which about a third consists of swampy areas.
